{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T03:05:37.084922+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T22:08:54.042473+00:00", "id": 13427227, "conceptrecid": "13427226", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13427227", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13427226", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13427227", "metadata": {"title": "Benign effects of logging on aerial insectivorous bats in Southeast Asia revealed by remote sensing technologies", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13427227", "publication_date": "2023", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Abstract\n            \n              \n                \n                  Logging is the most widespread disturbance in tropical forests, altering ecological communities and functions. However, many species can persist in logged forests, particularly where disturbance is low. Despite a growing understanding of how logging affects wildlife, there remains little information for Southeast Asia's bats\u2014in part due to major challenges in monitoring.\n                \n                \n                  We integrated remote sensing data from passive acoustic bat detectors with LiDAR\u2010derived measures of forest structure from a human\u2010modified landscape in Sabah, Borneo. Our appraisal of logging effects benefitted from a semi\u2010automated classifier of bat calls that vastly speeds up the analysis of acoustic recording data. We recorded 105,576 bat passes from 21 phonic groups across a habitat disturbance gradient, comprising old\u2010growth forest, repeatedly logged forest and tree plantations.\n                \n                \n                  We show that logging pressure (as depicted by changes to habitat quality, e.g. canopy height or shape) had negligible impact on the acoustic activity of bats. However, bat activity was higher in areas with a greater extent of high\u2010biomass forest, as well as areas with greater topographical ruggedness. Logged forest supported higher levels of activity for several common bat phonic groups compared to old\u2010growth forest. Across the landscape, plantations supported the lowest levels of bat activity, representing a threefold decrease compared to old\u2010growth forest, and several species were not recorded in this habitat.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    We found different call groups demonstrated different responses to forest disturbance. Sheath\u2010tailed bats (\n                    Emballonura\n                    spp.) were active across all habitat types and were the most resilient to logging. Edge/open foragers were more prevalent in highly forested and topographically rugged areas. Horseshoe and leaf\u2010nosed bats (flutter clutter foragers) demonstrated idiosyncratic responses to logging but were consistently absent from plantations.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  \n                    Synthesis and applications\n                    . Logged forests can provide an important refuge for many common bat species in Southeast Asia, but do not capture the full breadth of forest\u2010specialist species. Nevertheless, logged forests provide substantially better habitat for bats than tree plantations. While aerial insectivorous bats sampled via acoustic methods are poor indicators of forest disturbance overall, several species that respond predictably to logging could be targeted for biodiversity monitoring using acoustic and capture\u2010based methods.\n                  \n                \n              \n            \n          , \n            Ringkasan\n            \n              \n                \n                  Pembalakan merupakan gangguan yang paling meluas di hutan tropika, mengubah komuniti dan fungsi ekologi. Walau bagaimanapun, banyak spesies boleh bertahan di hutan yang telah dibalak, terutamanya apabila tahap gangguan adalah rendah. Walaupun pemahaman semakin meningkat tentang impak pembalakan terhadap hidupan liar, masih sedikit maklumat tentang kelawar Asia Tenggara \u2010 sebahagiannya disebabkan oleh cabaran utama dalam pemantauan.\n                \n                \n                  Kami menggabungkan data penderiaan jauh daripada pengesan kelawar akustik pasif dengan ukuran struktur hutan yang diperolehi melalui LiDAR daripada landskap yang diubah\u2010suai manusia di Sabah, Borneo. Penilaian kami terhadap kesan pembalakan mendapat manfaat daripada pengelas separa automatik bagi panggilan kelawar yang sangat mempercepatkan analisis data rakaman akustik. Kami merekodkan 105,576 lintasan kelawar daripada 21 kumpulan fonik merentasi kecerunan gangguan habitat, yang terdiri daripada hutan tua, hutan yang telah dibalak berulang kali dan ladang pokok.\n                \n                \n                  Kami menunjukkan bahawa tekanan pembalakan (seperti yang digambarkan oleh perubahan kepada kualiti habitat cth. ketinggian atau bentuk kanopi) tidak mempunyai kesan yang signifikan ke atas aktiviti akustik kelawar. Walau bagaimanapun, aktiviti kelawar adalah lebih tinggi di kawasan yang mempunyai keluasan hutan dengan biojisim yang lebih besar dan di kawasan yang mempunyai topografi yang lebih kasar. Hutan yang telah dibalak menyokong tahap aktiviti yang lebih tinggi untuk beberapa kumpulan fonik kelawar biasa berbanding dengan hutan tua. Secara keseluruhannya, kawasan ladang pokok menyokong tahap aktiviti kelawar yang paling rendah, iaitu mewakili penurunan sebanyak tiga kali ganda berbanding dengan hutan tua, dan terdapat beberapa spesies yang tidak direkodkan di habitat ini.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    Kami mendapati kumpulan panggilan yang berbeza menunjukkan respons yang berbeza terhadap gangguan hutan. Kelawar berekor sarung (\n                    Emballonura\n                    spp.) adalah aktif di semua jenis habitat dan paling berdaya tahan terhadap impak pembalakan. Kelawar dari kumpulan pencari makanan di habitat pinggir/terbuka lebih banyak ditemui di kawasan yang berhutan dan dengan topografi yang kasar. Kelawar tapak kuda dan kelawar berhidung daun (pemakan flutter clutter) menunjukkan respons yang unik terhadap pembalakan tetapi secara konsisten tidak dijumpai di kawasan ladang.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  \n                    Sintesis dan aplikasi.\n                    Hutan yang telah dibalak boleh menyediakan kawasan perlindungan yang penting kepada banyak spesies kelawar biasa di Asia Tenggara, tetapi ia tidak dapat menampung kesemua spesies yang hanya hidup di kawasan hutan. Sungguhpun demikian, hutan yang telah dibalak menyediakan habitat yang jauh lebih baik untuk kelawar berbanding dengan ladang pokok. Walaupun kelawar insektivor udara yang dijadikan sampel melalui kaedah akustik dalam kajian ini adalah penunjuk yang lemah terhadap impak gangguan habitat hutan secara keseluruhannya, beberapa spesies yang menunjukkan respons yang telah dijangka terhadap impak pembalakan boleh digunakan dalam pemantauan biodiversiti dengan menggunakan kaedah berasaskan akustik dan tangkapan.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Yoh, Natalie", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Seaman, Dave J. I.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Deere, Nicolas J.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Bernard, Henry", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Bicknell, Jake E.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Struebig, Matthew J.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/688835eb67faf3848d599ea3d42cbc65", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/127ae9ff1092e8073da69ecb649e898af7d796c01996ac8633ffe4a869c5df9e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/KVQUFC5F", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zoter